following nerves supplies the trachea and muscles for the vocal cords?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phrenic nerve","Vagus nerve","Great auricular nerve","Accessory nerve","Transverse cervical nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve X) is the correct answer. It provides sensory and motor innervation to the trachea and larynx, including the muscles of the vocal cords. The intrinsic muscles of the larynx (except the cricothyroid) are innervated by the recurrent laryngeal nerve, a branch of the vagus nerve. The cricothyroid muscle is innervated by the external branch of the superior laryngeal nerve, another branch of the vagus nerve. The vagus nerve plays a crucial role in regulating breathing and speech. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ephrenic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily innervates the diaphragm and is not involved in the innervation of the trachea or vocal cords. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egreat auricular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a cutaneous nerve that supplies sensation to the skin over the parotid gland and the external ear. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccessory nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve XI) innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etransverse cervical nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a cutaneous nerve that provides sensory innervation to the anterior neck region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the innervation of the trachea and vocal cords is essential for comprehending various clinical conditions affecting voice production and respiratory function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vagus nerve (cranial nerve X) provides sensory and motor innervation to the trachea and larynx, including the muscles of the vocal cords."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Rea, P. Essential clinically applied anatomy of the peripheral nervous system in the head and neck. 2016. Chapter 2 - Head. Academic Press. Available fro: https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-12-803633-4.00002-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47740"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14393"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47740"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T16:44:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T16:45:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7088"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62293"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"descri